Hey just posting fast since I work soon but I can update later if needed.

Contracts in the contract building do not show up when I boot the game with the .25 versions of either

Texture Replacer

Active Texture Management

I am also running:

  • Near future solar
  • Near future construction
  • TAC
  • Kerbal alarm clock
  • Kerbal joint replacement
  • Mission controller
  • Part catalog
  • Precise node
  • Procedural wings
  • Procedural fairings
  • Contracts window
  • Final frontier
  • DMagic Orbital
  • Engineer Redux
  • Mechjeb (minimal)

This is in 32 bit since those mods aren't supporting 64.

I have tested these others and the contracts show up; things are fine. It is the two texture replacement mods that cause issue.

I let the Active team know but just posting here for any possible expedition.

Thanks guys!

----------------

But this goes against the whole idea of even using ActiveText.

So it has to be one of the only mods to be installed to allow me contracts.

As soon as I enable the Active Texture Management, contracts are invisible altogether. This is using latest versions of both.

I will test further this afternoon to find more possible conflicts.

Well, there are a number of exceptions in your log:

1. PartCatalog appears to be failing to load.

2. The Contracts mod is failing to load the RealChute agency texture near the end of the loading process.

3. Active Texture Management is giving a null reference exception immediately after number 2.

4. TAC life support is giving an exception in Tac.AddLifeSupport.EvaAddPartModule though this appears to be expected behaviour.

5. MissionController is giving a NullReferenceException when it is destroyed.

6. RealChute is giving a NullReferenceException when it is destroyed (trying to remove itself from the stock toolbar).

My suggestions based on this would be:

1. Remove PartCatalog as it doesn't appear to be working.

2. Your version of Contracts Window+ is out of date. Update it to 2.2. Also your version of RealChute is out of date so update that to the latest version too.

3. Make sure that Active Texture Management is up to date. There was a new release 20 hours ago (3 and a half hours after your original post).

4. ModuleManager has been updated to 2.5.1.0 so update that too.
